<node CREATED="1189103822843" FOLDED="true" ID="Freemind_Link_1198155016" LINK="http://www.blendernewbies.com/tutorials/swf/decaling_basics/decaling_basics.html" MODIFIED="1189103943250" TEXT="Basic Decaling in Blender">
<node CREATED="1189103841843" ID="Freemind_Link_487613148" MODIFIED="1189103984609" TEXT="Well, here&apos;s another Blender tutorial! This time we take a look at how to apply decals to a 3D mesh object. It&apos;s really very simple but, there are a couple of snags you might run into and I demonstrate how to resolve those issues.&#xa;&#xa;http://www.blendernewbies.com/tutorials/swf/decaling_basics/decaling_basics.zip"/>
<node CREATED="1189103901765" FOLDED="true" ID="Freemind_Link_1708934161" MODIFIED="1189103909656" TEXT="script text">
<node CREATED="1189103911468" ID="Freemind_Link_1400217416" MODIFIED="1189103920359" TEXT="BASIC DECALING IN BLENDER&#xa;&#xa;Hello, and welcome to another Blendernewbies tutorial! In this session we&apos;ll be taking a look at how to do basic decaling in Blender.&#xa;&#xa;We&apos;ll be applying the Blender logo to the character&apos;s shirt using the decaling technique. Since this technique is almost the same as simply applying a texture to an object, once mastered, it&apos;s very fast.&#xa;&#xa;Let&apos;s get to it.&#xa;&#xa;First, you want to select the object that will have the decal applied. In this case, we want to select the character&apos;s body where I have multiple materials already applied.&#xa;&#xa;I&apos;m using an object that already has multiple materials because I want to demonstrate this technique in a realistic scenario. When you want to apply a decal to an object, more than likely that object will already have some materials in place.&#xa;&#xa;So, with our object selected, we switch to the Editing buttons window, and because this object has multiple materials, we need to locate the appropriate material so that the decal can be seen where we intend to place it. In this case, we look for the material called &quot;shirt&quot;. If we used the material assigned to the short pants area, we wouldn&apos;t see our decal in the shirt material area. So, we make sure that the current material is set to &quot;shirt&quot;.&#xa;&#xa;Now, we go to the Shading buttons window and then, Materials. In the Texture panel,  we click &quot;Add New&quot; to add a new Texture Channel. This is where we&apos;ll place the image for our decal. Let&apos;s name this channel &quot;decal&quot;. Now let&apos;s go to the Texture  buttons window and set the Texture Type to &quot;Image&quot;. On the Image panel, select your  image file from the list or click Load to browse for the file. And, let&apos;s do a quick render and take a look at what we have so far.&#xa;&#xa;You can see that the Blender logo has been applied to the mesh within the areas that have the &quot;shirt&quot; material.&#xa;&#xa;Now, we want the logo to be right here on the character&apos;s shirt. So, from the Front view, let&apos;s add an Empty. We can see that the Empty has been added where the 3D Cursor is located. Let&apos;s move it out along the global y-axis and scale it down a little. Notice that the Empty&apos;s z-axis is oriented along the global y-axis. That&apos;s because we created it from the Front view and in Blender the Local z-axis of newly created objects is based on the viewport angle.&#xa;&#xa;Now, let&apos;s move the Empty up a little. The z-axis of the Empty object is important because the image will be projected along its z-axis.&#xa;&#xa;Let&apos;s name the Empty &quot;decal_target&quot;. We need to remember this name because we&apos;ll be using it in just a few seconds.&#xa;&#xa;With our character selected, let&apos;s go to the Shading buttons window and then the Material buttons tab. I&apos;m setting the texture preview type to Plane, so it&apos;s easier to see our decal texture.&#xa;&#xa;Now we go to the Map Input panel. We&apos;ll be setting the Map Input type to be Object. As you can see from the tooltip, this will use the linked object&apos;s coordinates for the texture&apos;s coordinates. In other words, we will tell Blender to use the Empty as the linked object and that will cause the texture&apos;s coordinates to be controlled by the Empty.&#xa;&#xa;So, we select the Object input type, and in the text field next to it, we type in the name of the Empty which is &quot;decal_target&quot;. BTW, you can select an object and see its name in the lower left corner of the window.&#xa;&#xa;Okay...&#xa;&#xa;Let&apos;s do a render to see what we get. We can see that our logo is now mapped a little bit better than before. But, it&apos;s still not what we&apos;re looking for so, let&apos;s adjust some things.&#xa;&#xa;BTW, I accidentally edited out something that needs explaining. Let&apos;s split this window and change it to &quot;UV/Image Editor&quot;. I&apos;m doing this so that we can get our render to display within a Blender window instead of the usual floating Render window. Seeing the render right beside our workspace is one way to make things a little bit easier when working on something like this. You could also use a Preview window. So anyway, having set the window type to UV/Image Editor, we have to set the image that we want displayed. In this case, we want it to always show the Render Result. However, there&apos;s one little catch to getting this to work...you have to have actually rendered something before you will see the Render Result option listed. So, if you&apos;re working on something where you&apos;ve already done some rendering, you&apos;ll see this option in the listing. If you&apos;ve just started a new scene and decide that you want to create this type of layout, you won&apos;t have this option listed until you have a camera setup and have actually rendered something.&#xa;&#xa;I&apos;m going bring in my camera and lights on layer 6...In the Scene buttons window, you find a dropdown listing to set where the render results are shown. I&apos;m setting it to Render Window, the Blender default, and you can see we get the familiar Render Window. If I set it to Image Editor, the render results will be displayed in the UV/Image Editor.&#xa;&#xa;Okay, now that we&apos;ve got our render results conveniently placed inside the Image Editor, let&apos;s finish up our decaling.&#xa;&#xa;We see that our image is being tiled within the targeted area and that&apos;s not what we want. So, let&apos;s correct this by going to the Texture buttons window (make sure the object is selected). On the Map Image panel, we want to use the Clip option. This will make any area beyond the original image&apos;s boundary, transparent. Right now, it&apos;s set to Repeat which explains the tiling effect that we&apos;re getting.&#xa;&#xa;Notice that selecting the Clip option will deselect the Repeat option.&#xa;&#xa;And, let&apos;s do a render to see the results.&#xa;&#xa;Okay, now we have a non-repeating image that is transparent in all areas outside of the decal image&apos;s borders.&#xa;&#xa;We now want to scale it down a little by selecting the Empty that is controlling our decal, and scale it appropriately. Another quick render and you can see that we are controlling the size of the image by scaling the Empty object.&#xa;&#xa;We can also control the rotation angle of the decaled image by adjusting the Empty.&#xa;&#xa;Let&apos;s do another render...&#xa;&#xa;Okay...&#xa;&#xa;Before we continue, I&apos;m going to reset the rotation of the Empty because we don&apos;t want the logo to be at an angle.&#xa;&#xa;We want to make sure we have our mesh object selected and, let&apos;s hide the manipulator.&#xa;&#xa;Okay, we can still see the white background area of our decal image and that&apos;s not what we want for this situation. To solve that, we turn on the UseAlpha option on the Map Image panel. And, let&apos;s render the results.&#xa;&#xa;Now, we know that we just told Blender to use the image&apos;s alpha channel but, we&apos;re still seeing the white background. That means our decal image does not have an Alpha channel that Blender can use. This is a common problem when decaling so, let&apos;s look at how to solve it.&#xa;&#xa;I&apos;m switching to a graphics application called PhotoPlus but, you can use GIMP, Photoshop, or whatever. All we want to do is give our image an alpha channel. I have a folder already setup pointing to our image and I&apos;m just going to drag-drop it into the graphics application.&#xa;&#xa;I&apos;m going to make this a layer and then use the magic wand tool to select only the white area of the image. I&apos;m setting the color selection tolerance to 25 so we get a nice and clean selection. Okay...now we just delete the white areas that have been selected, leaving us with transparent areas instead.&#xa;&#xa;Notice that the file format is PNG. You want to make sure that you use a file format that supports transparency. PNG is a good format so we&apos;ll stick with that.&#xa;&#xa;Now, I&apos;m just making sure that the PNG file format is setup to use 32-bit depth which is required if you want to include the alpha channel that we just created.&#xa;&#xa;Now, I&apos;m going to give the file a better name so we don&apos;t confuse it with the original file. Let&apos;s use &quot;blender_logo_alpha&quot;.&#xa;&#xa;And, we&apos;re done!&#xa;&#xa;Now, back in Blender, we need to replace our existing decal image with the new one containing the alpha channel. We can see a difference in the preview already. Let&apos;s turn off UseAlpha for a second and do a quick render. We can see that without the UseAlpha option, even our new decal image still shows a white background.&#xa;&#xa;Let&apos;s enable UseAlpha, notice the preview image changed, and let&apos;s do another render.&#xa;&#xa;Now, that&apos;s what we want! A nice, clean decal with the desired alpha channel.&#xa;&#xa;Using our Empty, let&apos;s finish applying the decal by adjusting the scaling and position.&#xa;&#xa;I&apos;m going to reposition the camera for a better view...we&apos;ll fix the decal&apos;s vertical stretching by scaling the Empty along the global z-axis...make it a little bit larger...and, move it up a little along the global z-axis. Now, finalize the camera position and do one more render...and we&apos;re finished!&#xa;&#xa;We now have a nice Blender logo decaled onto the character&apos;s shirt.&#xa;&#xa;QUICK REVIEW&#xa;&#xa;The process of applying a decal to an object in Blender normally would take less than a minute. However, I wanted to go through the process in a way that would demonstrate some of the issues you might encounter when first learning this and also how to deal with those issues.&#xa;&#xa;Now, let&apos;s review what we&apos;ve covered:&#xa;&#xa;First, you want to add the decal image as a texture to the target mesh object. In the Map Input panel, enable the UseAlpha and Clip options.&#xa;&#xa;Next, add an Empty with the z-axis pointed away from the mesh. The x-y axis defines the orientation of the decal image. Think of the z-axis as a line of projection for the decal image onto the mesh object.&#xa;&#xa;Finally, with the mesh object selected, go to the Map Input field and set the input type to Object. In the blank field to the right of the button, enter the name of the Empty object.&#xa;&#xa;Remember that the Empty object now controls the location, rotation, and scaling of the decal image on your mesh object.&#xa;&#xa;&#xa;&#xa;That all!&#xa;&#xa;Thanks for Watching!&#xa;&#xa;"/>
</node>
</node>
