<node CREATED="1189345958718" FOLDED="true" ID="Freemind_Link_1618491742" MODIFIED="1189345958718" TEXT="a few things you need to know:">
<node CREATED="1189346052953" ID="Freemind_Link_1705672585" MODIFIED="1189346052953" TEXT="1.) Gelato doesn&apos;t support normal-mapping, out of the box. There are a couple of threads on the topic here on the forums (including partial code for implementing a normal map shader, if you&apos;ve got any programming chops)."/>
<node CREATED="1189346052953" MODIFIED="1189346052953" TEXT="2.) Gelato does include displacement shaders. These are true displacement, and not just bump-mapping. That is, for example, if you look at your object edge-on, you will really see that the surface is deformed. Personally, I think the result looks more natural than normal mapping, but it does require some tender loving care to tune it just right. One thing to be aware of is that since it&apos;s a true displacement, your object may end up clipping through other objects, where it did not previously. (Also, your mistakes can turn out really funny. A small typo gave me an exploding eyeball in one render. laugh.gif )"/>
<node CREATED="1189346052953" ID="Freemind_Link_1549172820" MODIFIED="1189346083515" TEXT="3.) If you&apos;re using ZBrush, it can export displacement maps. If you have a normal map you&apos;d like to use (but lack the generator), you may or may not be able to convert it. The trouble is that normal maps don&apos;t have any depth data -- just normal data. If it was a flat normal map, meant to be applied just to the surface of something, you may get some good results by using this trick:&#xa;http://christianstoray.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=26&amp;Itemid=32"/>
<node CREATED="1189346092265" MODIFIED="1189346092265" TEXT="4.) I&apos;m not sure that the Gelato documentation is correct with respect to displacement maps. They say that 50% gray is the unperturbed level. But, in all of my tests, black was the unperturbed level. I&apos;m not sure how to explain this discrepancy."/>
<node CREATED="1189346099765" ID="Freemind_Link_335370353" MODIFIED="1189346099765" TEXT="5.) The Gelato Blender exporter, in its current form, does not support any of the displacement shaders. These have to be placed in a separate shader group from the surface shaders. Our multi-shader version of XYZ&apos;s exporter will support them, but we&apos;re still working on that part."/>
<node CREATED="1189346121953" MODIFIED="1189346121953" TEXT="6.) If you really must use some feature that isn&apos;t supported in the exporter yet, you can hand-edit your pyg files after you export them. Though this is a big hassle, if you&apos;re still actively developing your models."/>
</node>
